If you liked that popular book, try THIS book The Selection by Kierra Cass -> The Jewel by Amy Ewing I read this book a few years back. It was one of the first serieses that excited me after the downfall of the dystopian era. (The Hunger Games, Divergent, The Selection, etc.) I am a huge dystopian fan, and if youâ€™re looking for a wonderful way to relive this phase, please pick up this series.  The Invisible Life of Addie Larue by V.E. Schwab -> How to Stop Time by Matt Haig This book is written by the author of the booktok book The Midnight Library, another one of my favorites. This book is impeccably written and colorfully emotional, flashing from past to present as we watch our main character fall into a painful love in which he cannot hold on to. If He Had Been With Me by Laura Nowlin -> The Light We Lost by Jill Santopolo These two books have one major element in common: sadness. I found this book more relatable than I wanted to, reading it while going through my first and only real breakup. The characters in this book feel so real and fall into a love that is innocent and complicated and natural and full of chemistry. I have yet to find a book that makes me feel the way this one did. The love story in this book is pungent and sharp and will leave you feeling equally as hopeful and hopeless. Archer's Voice by Mia Sheridan -> Only Love Can Hurt Like This by Paige Toon This book is a small town romance done well. It deviates from the general predictions we see constantly within the trope, but fulfills us in the areas we rely on. This book not only offers a beautiful romance, but a blossoming familial story.
